I'm running this code from Jupyter Notebook on my local pc: Windows 10, HP Elitebook 840 G3, 32 GB Ram, System 64bit with Python 3.6.0, Anaconda and SASPy 2.2.6. I have SAS on local PC with SAS 9.4 TS Level 1M4.

import pandas as pd
import saspy
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
sas1 = saspy.SASsession(cfgname='winlocal')
sas1.saslib('Mylib', path="C:\\tmp")
dataset_sas=sas1.sasdata('NyTest','mylib')
t=dataset_sas.to_df()

The dataset in “Mylib” contains 40.000 observations and 8 variables and are created by this code in SAS Base:

libname Mylib "C:\tmp";

data Mylib.NyTest ;
 Length t1 t2 t3 8. t4 t5 $100. t6 8.;
 do i=1 to 40000;
 t1=1;
 t2=.;
 t3=3;
 t4='ÆØÅ -678';
 t5='ÆØÅ-678';
 t6=.;
 t7='ÆØÅ- 678 ';
 output;
 end;
run;

The SAS dataset has encoding lik “wlatin1 Western (Windows)” and as you can see it contains some fields with Norwegian special characters “ÆØÅ”.

When I run the code in Python, the process ends with log: “SAS process has terminated unexpectedly. RC from wait was: 0”.

Strangely, if I run the SAS code and replace the "ÆØÅ" with "ABC" or just drop the fields “t6”, “t7” and “i” like this: “data Mylib.NyTest (drop=  t6 t7 i);”) the code in Python/Jupyter Notebook runs successful and without error. Even if I do not drop “t4 “and “t5” which also contains special characters.

